.TH HTFILEFS 4
.SH NAME
htfilefs \- HTTP file file system
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B ip/htfilefs
[
.B -9d
]
[
.B -b
.I count
]
[
.B -x
.I netstk
]
[
.B -m
.I mtpt
]
[
.B -s
.I serv
]
.I URI
.SH DESCRIPTION
.I Htfilefs
serves locally the file specified as
.I URI
and opens a srv file, as default
.BR /srv/htfile.
.PP
The options
.B -9
and
.B -d
are for application and 9p debugging,
.B -b
tells
.I Htfilefs
to cache
.I count
blocks,
.B -x
specifies the network stack,
.B -m
tells
.I Htfilefs
where to mount itself on startup and
.B -s
specifies a different srv file than the default (htfile).
.SH EXAMPLE
For mounting in the current Plan 9 ISO from
.BR 9grid.de
as /n/cdrom, do:
.IP
.EX
ip/htfilefs -m tmp http://www.9grid.de/plan9/plan9.iso;
9660srv;
mount /srv/9660 /n/cdrom /mnt/plan9.iso;
.EE
.SH SOURCE
.B /sys/src/cmd/ip/htfilefs.c
.SH BUGS
.PP
.I Htfilefs
never clears old blocks, except when the cache gets full.
.SH HISTORY
Htfilefs was written by Christoph Lohmann and it is based on
the structure of
.I sshnet(1).

